time of the cosmos. Both could be seen as united in the world soul as the seat of subjective time on a cosmic scale. But no solution to the problem was final. No theory gained general acceptance. The book shows the fascinating variety and plurality of ideas about time and soul throughout antiquity. Throughout antiquity, the problem of time and soul remained as intriguing as it proved intractable.  aIssued also in print.  afunded by Einstein Center Chronoi  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aNeoplatonism. 0aTime perception. 4aAristoteles. 4aAugustinus, Aurelius. 4aZeitverständnis. 7aRELIGION / Ancient.2bisacsh  aAristotle.  aEarly Christianity.  aNeoplatonism.  atime perception.2 aEinstein Center Chronoiefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2022 Part 1z978311076682008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022 Englishz978311099389908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2022z9783110994810oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2022 Englishz978311099291508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2022z9783110992878oZDB-23-DGD0 cEPUBz97831106927610 cprintz978311069272340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9783110692754zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110692754zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110692754/original  a978-3-11-076682-0 DG Plus DeG Package 2022 Part 1b2022  a978-3-11-099291-5 EBOOK PACKAGE Class